Meals for Children: The ASD is providing breakfast and lunch for all children ages 1-18. No paperwork is required and adults may pick up meals for children. In addition to serving at all schools between 11:10 and 12:40, we are delivering to select bus stops throughout the ASD.

To locate a bus stop near you for school meals, please follow the link to enter your address. https://www.auburn.wednet.edu/Page/420

If no bus stop is listed, the address is not on a delivery route. Please go to the closest school to pick up meals.

A small army of volunteers, staff and local business partners packed and delivered 3,000 food boxes to Auburn families this week.

The food helped bridge the gap between the summer meals program and the start of the new school year. Thank you to everyone who made this happen, especially our community partners- Auburn Public Schools Foundation, Penny's Salsa, Safeway, Smith Brothers Farms, Sterino Farms, Mosby Farms and Auburn Dairy.

post_text: Interested in free preschool? Auburn School District has an Early Childhood Education Assistance Program (ECEAP) with 6 locations, serving eligible children ages 3-5. ECEAP serves families who are low-income, adopted/foster/kinship care, or have children with active IEPs. ECEAP will begin the school year in a distance learning format. Families enrolled in ECEAP have access to free meals, family support services, parent education opportunities, and high quality early learning instruction. For applications or questions about the program, please call a family support specialist at (253) 931-4943, (253) 939-2998 or email ECEAP@auburn.wednet.edu. Multi-lingual support available.

post_text:
A message from Superintendent Spicciati:

Dear ASD Community,

This week has brought a conversation to our nation that has been below the surface for too long. I am crushed by the pain carried by so many in our community. We shouldn’t wait for another horrific act to trigger our awareness. We must call out racism when we see it, and make it visible when we cannot. I am proud of our work for educational equity – for the success of each and every young person in our school community – and I look forward to partnering with all of you to realize our dream of graduating every student prepared for their future.

Dr. Alan Spicciati
Superintendent

I am proud of our work for educational equity – for the success of each and every young person in our school community – and I look forward to partnering with all of you to realize our dream of graduating every student prepared for their future.

Dr. Alan Spicciati
Superintendent

REMINDER: Auburn School District playgrounds, courts and fields are closed to the public. This also applies to community members who have checked out access keys.

This means:
"Touch surfaces" including playground structures and swing sets are closed
All courts are closed
All locked fields are closed
Everyone must maintain social distancing
Groups of people may not gather
Open spaces that are normally available remain available for activities such as walking and biking

Please observe these rules so we can all do our part to slow the spread.

March 19 at 2:00 PM ·

"Touch surfaces" including playground structures and swing sets are closed
All courts are closed
Open spaces that are normally available remain available for activities such as walking and biking
Everyone must maintain social distancing
Groups of people may not gather

Please observe these rules so we can all do our part to slow the spread.

We believe it's important to share this warning from the health department. The drug Fentanyl is killing young people in King County. This dangerous drug may have been found in street-sold Oxycodone or Percocet.

To stay safe and prevent an overdose remember:

Don’t use drugs.
Don’t use pills/powders from the street or that have been purchased online.
Call 911 if someone overdoses, you won’t be in trouble.

More info @ www.stopoverdose.org

post_text: Please read what Mr. Keller posted. We have an amazing community!
shared_text:
Brian Keller is with Luke Peterson and 2 others.
February 11 at 9:43 PM ·

Sometimes things happen at all schools that give a false impression of what a school is like. I want to give a true impression of my school, Auburn High. Tonight I watched two teams of amazing kids play hard, show sportsmanship and kindness to each other. I watched a student body show up big to support them, and go wild with every basket from both teams. I watched in season coaches give up their non existent time to ref the game. I watched staff members volunteering to coach, organize, bring their families to watch, and cheer on all these great students. I watched our district superintendent and cabinet show up. I watched our administration cheering on our kids. I watched our band volunteer to play, dance teams to dance, and community members come out to be a part of it all. THAT is what our school’s narrative is! That is why after so long I still love my job and my alma-mater! Go Trojans!

post_text:
The ASD is accepting referrals for the 2020-2021 Highly Capable Program, a program that serves exceptionally intelligent, intellectually gifted students whose needs may not be easily met in the general education setting.

Once a student is identified as highly capable, he/she is entitled to Highly Capable program services from the date of eligibility through graduation; annual testing is not required. Nominations close January 17, 2020.

Screening considers nominees who are currently in grades kindergarten through 11. Selection for highly capable programs reflects state guidelines for identifying intellectually gifted students.

If you feel your child should participate in further testing, but doesn’t meet screening criteria, you may nominate your child.

Nomination forms are available in school counseling offices or at www.auburn.wednet.edu, For Families/Highly Capable/Highly Capable Forms

Questions? Contact your student's counselor or Adam Ladage
aladage@auburn.wednet.edu (253) 931-4950

This time of year, weather can be unpredictable and can impact school schedules, bus routes and activities. In the ASD, we communicate school schedule changes via a variety of tools.

• The School Messenger phone calling system will call all staff and families. Please update your phone number with your student's school.
• The ASD website will show changes. Limited transportation routes can be found under Quick Links.
• FlashAlert. If you have signed up for FlashAlert, you will receive an email and/or push notification.
• The ASD Facebook page will be updated.
• The ASD Twitter feed will be updated.
• Local radio and TV stations also will provide information regarding school schedule changes.

Please contact the Communications Department with any questions at communications@auburn.wednet.edu

Community Prevention and Wellness Initiative (CPWI) Community Survey 2019

Auburn Prevention Coalition
September 5, 2019 at 9:39 AM ·

The Auburn Prevention Coalition wants to hear from you! We are asking you to participate in a confidential community survey if you are 18 or older and live or work in the city of Auburn!

The survey is about concerns related to substance abuse among youth in the Auburn area. We will use the data to guide our work to develop effective substance abuse prevention programs within the Auburn School District and our community. The survey is completely voluntary and anonymous. We will not know your identity and you are able to skip questions or stop the survey at any point. The survey will take approximately 10 minutes to complete.

We believe it's important to share this warning from the health department. The drug Fentanyl is killing King County residents. Recently, six young people have passed away due to this dangerous drug that may have been found in street-sold Oxycodone or Percocet.

To stay safe and prevent an overdose remember:

Don’t use drugs.
Don’t use pills/powders from the street or that have been purchased online.
Call 911 if someone overdoses, you won’t be in trouble.
